Initiation of Coverage

 

NextDC

Initiating a space & time continuum

Initiate with BUY on Australia's leading data centre operator

NXT is one of the largest neutral data centre operators in Aus and the only one with a national footprint. Listed in Dec-10, NXT is now entering a new stage of its life as the initial construction phase ends and revenue momentum begins to builds. With this in mind, NXT needs to be assessed from a highly fundamental perspective, and we think significant valuation upside remains on a risk-reward basis over the next 2yrs. We forecast NXT to hit EBITDA breakeven in 1H15 (guidance) & reach NPAT +ive by FY17e.

Unique investment exposure to structural technology trends

The underlying thesis for investing in colocation is driven by a number of secular trends, including 1) growth in data centre based IP traffic; 2) outsourcing/consolidation of smaller legacy data centres; 3) increasing power and cooling requirements that are difficult for in-house solutions to handle; 4) cloud technology maturity driving adoption of as-a-service delivery models; and 5) growth in the importance of interconnectivity which can be established within neutral colocation ecosystems.

Trading at discount to existing portfolio valuation excluding TV + optionality

As an investment, we think data centres should exhibits infrastructure-like free-cash-flow attributes, hence conventional earnings multiple bases valuation methods are less applicable in our view. Using project IRR, EV/IC and project-based DCF, we value NXT's existing portfolio at $1.95 to $2.05 over ~25yr project-life. Practically, data centres should also have modest terminal value based on replacement cost in our view (similar to power stations), given site location and available network connectivity. In addition to its existing portfolio, NXT (as an established operator) offers additional optionality from potential new DC builds, capital structure optimisation and/or capital management.

Valuation: Finite DCF $2.05 + $0.20 TV (based on ~40% replacement cost)

Our $2.25 price-target is based on a 25yr DCF of NXT's existing portfolio ($2.05) plus terminal value ($0.20) using ~40% future replacement cost. Furthermore, ~$0.50 of future development optionality is feasible in our view. At ~$1.60, we estimate NXT is trading on ~14.5% project IRR and ~1.0x EV/IC (adjusted for deployable capital).

Investment case

NXT is one of the largest neutral data centre operators in Australia and the only one with a national footprint. The company is entering a new phase of its life cycle as the initial construction phase ends and revenue momentum begins to gain critical mass.

In this context, we think NXT needs to be assessed from a highly fundamental perspective and significant valuation upside exists on a risk-reward basis over the next ~2yrs in our view.

In the longer term, we think NXT is also exposed to a number of thematics in the technology space. The growth in colocation is driven by a number of structural trends, including:
1) growth in data centre based IP traffic;
2) outsourcing/consolidation of smaller legacy data centres;
3) increasing datacentre power and cooling requirements;
4) maturity of cloud technology driving adoption of as-a-service delivery models; and
5) the growing importance of interconnectivity within colocation ecosystems
j

Upside scenario

Our bull-case valuation scenario for NXT is ~$3.10, based on ~$2.20 value for the existing data centre portfolio (~1.5x EV/IC), ~$0.40 terminal value (80% future replacement cost) and ~$0.50 new data centre build-out value optionality.

Downside scenario

Our bear-case valuation scenario for NXT is ~$1.95, based on target ~12% project IRR with nil terminal value assumed after ~25 years of useful, and nil option value from potential new data centre development.

Business description

NXT is Australia's leading DCaaS (Data-Centre-as-a-Service) colocation provider, operating the only national footprint with multiple data centres in major capital cities. NXT listed on the ASX in Dec-2010 with the aim to develop the next generation of large scale data centres in Australia. Since then NXT has completed construction of all 5 data centres it currently operates, financed from IPO proceeds, additional equity injections and capital recycling via sale and leaseback of land.

Industry outlook

At the end of 2013 the colocation services market grew to ~$700m in Australia, representing +17% growth over 2012; the overall technical foot print increasing +16% by ~31k sqm. Industry forecasts project +11.7% CAGR for technical space from ~230k sqm in 2013 to ~500k sqm in 2017, accompanied by revenue CAGR of +13.9% to ~$1.7bn from ~$0.7b.

Simplifying data centres as an investment

We consider data centres (DC) as an asset type which exhibits many quasi-infrastructure attributes.

However unlike traditional utilities or transport infrastructure where relative certainty of volume or pricing (or both) exists, DCs face higher revenue risks given they are neither monopolistic nor regulated. Nevertheless we recognise a DC does have characteristics which reduce revenue volatility significantly once it is sufficiently contracted (such as the sticky network nature of customers, capex & location barriers for new builds, and the economies of scale in operating costs).

In essence, a DC's theoretical FCF profile over its asset life should be similar to a typical infrastructure asset in our view (albeit with higher risks). To demonstrate this, we have constructed a simple stimulation for a hypothetical DC over a ~25yr asset life using generic assumptions. Similar to infrastructure, common differences between a DC and an industrial type business model include:

Heavy upfront construction and/or capacity fit-out capex in the first few years.

Initial sales from signing foundation customers can produce low revenue yields, but this should improve as the DC ecosystem gains critical mass.

Relatively fixed cost base results in material operating leverage as capital utilisation increases, followed by stable CPI linked pricing and cost escalation.

Maintenance capex and O&M costs represent a low % of revenue and deprecation (without assuming additional capex to extend useful life).

Similar to toll roads or power generators, initial green-field development risks are significant, but the cost of capital should fall once the revenue base matures (as a brownfield asset). Accordingly over time, we think the gearing level of a DC can change materially to reflect capital structure efficiency.

Figure 1: Simulated enterprise FCF profile of a generic DC over a finite asset life

Source: UBSe

How to value NXT?

Lessons from the simulation exercise

As a benchmarking exercise, our simulation model for a standalone DC generated ~14% project IRR (with nil terminal value). Key operational assumptions include:

Fit-out capex of ~$9-10m per MW of capacity

90% of capacity contracted in ~7 years after opening

Yield per MW increasing from ~$3m to ~$6m, ramping up over ~7 years

Direct cost stabilising at ~20% of revenue (implying ~60-65% EBITDA margins)

No maintenance capex for ~5 years after opening, followed by O&M expenditure being capitalised at ~2-3% of revenue.

Using a 10-11% WACC, the simulation implied an EV/IC (invested capital) of 1.3-1.5x. EV/IC essentially measures the DCF of +ive future project cash inflows vs. DCF of initial ive cash outflows, representing the NPV uplift (i.e. return) on the investment made today (i.e. every $1 invested generates $0.30-0.50 of returns).

Can be applied to NXT

As a starting point, we think each of NXT's DCs should exhibit similar FCF profiles over their useful lives, overlaid with NXT's corporate expenses. Reinvestment in the latter stages of each DC's asset life is feasible to replenish the productive asset base, with the aim of extending their respective asset lives (but we have not factored this explicitly in our modelling).

Figure 2: UBSe NXT revenue application & EV FCF generation (assuming 25yr DC life)

Source: UBSe

Importantly, we believe NXT's valuation should not be viewed through an 'earning multiple' lens (which is better suited to traditional industrial / trading businesses).

Leaving aside terminal value and future development optionality as separate considerations for later, we first focus on three valuation tools which are better suited to valuing the finite project life cash-flows NXT can generate: 1) Project IRR targets, 2) EV/ IC (enterprise value to invested capital) on a mature build-out basis, and 3) DCF (with and without a terminal value).

Key valuation inputs to consider

Figure 3: UBSe MW contract vs price

Source: UBSe

MW yield vs. contracted MW: how will NXT's contracted MW growth profile shift in relation to $/MW yield? New NXT sales are already shifting to higher pricing after a period of signing foundation contracts with large channel partners. This increasing yield should be conjunction with moderate contracted MW growth; UBSe ~90% of existing DC's capacity to be sold by FY22.

Longer term market dynamics: Industry forecasts expect outsourced DC industry revenue to see solid growth at ~14% CAGR over the next ~5 years, driven by structural shifts in cloud adoption and changes to legacy IT architecture. As a relatively earlier-mover we expect NXT to face moderate competition with above average prospect of taking market share, particularly as smaller DCs physically consolidate into larger dedicated technical spaces.

So where is the estimated mature revenue & earnings level? We estimate existing capacity to be ~75% contracted (~30MW) at an average yield of >$5m/MW by FY18/19, and ~90% contracted (~36MW) at ~$6.2m/MW by FY22. We estimate this is below the price level implied by industry forecasts and assume little change in current kW/rack density. In FY21/22, we expect NXT to be generating ~$200-220m of revenue and $100-110m of EBITDA.

Figure 4: UBSe NXT MW contract utilisation profile vs. capex (assuming finite ~25yr life)

Source: UBSe, NXT

Reinvestment capex & asset life: NXT's near-term fit-out capex is relatively easy to forecast. However longer-term maintenance capex levels and the corresponding DC asset life (without factoring in significant replacement) capex is less clear at present in our view.

Terminal value: It is unknown how much hardware replacement is necessary for an aged DC to continue operating on a similar earnings yield beyond its accounting useful life. However on balance we think it is highly likely DCs will have residual value at the end of their accounting useful life, considering:

1) Reinvestment to extend useful life is likely lower than a complete new build

2) Brand value of the operator to retain clients (in new or rebuilt DC)

3) Inherent value of the DC location / network connectivity / ecosystem

Similar to a generic power station or wind-farm project, we think a DC's terminal value should be calculated as a % of replacement cost (a methodology employed in the utilities sector).

So what's priced in?

1) Project IRR: market implies ~13-15%, UBS target ~12%

We estimate NXT's current share price of ~$1.60 implies ~13.6% project IRR for NXT's existing DC footprint without incorporating any terminal value after ~25yrs. If including ~20% to ~70% estimated future replacement cost as terminal value, we estimate NXT would be trading on an implied IRR of 13.5-15%.

UBS view: We target ~12% project IRR as a reasonable level of return (note this measure is comparable to a sustainable post-tax ROIC) without a terminal value, the implied valuation is $1.95 per share. Using ~40% replacement cost as the terminal value - mainly for electrical (40-50% of new build) and some mechanical capex (20-30% of new build) - the implied valuation is $2.06 per share.

We show sensitivity of share price and assumed terminal value vs. implied IRR below (i.e. lower the share price and higher terminal value = higher return).

Figure 5: Sensitivity of NXT IRR to share price and terminal value

Source: UBSe

2) EV/IC: UBSe NXT trading on ~1.0x vs. ~1.4x target

Using a headline EV (market cap + net debt) to invested capital (net equity + net debt) ratio, NXT appears to be trading on ~1.4x book already. However this simplistic calculation is flawed in our view because:

It does not reflect the expected capital deployment in the medium term, and

It includes ive retained earnings which reduces shareholder capital (reflecting a timing mismatch of when the equity funds are expected to generate returns).

UBS view: A more appropriate EV / IC multiple should be based on look-through 'capital deployable' based on committed capex and existing funding available. Specifically we use gross shareholder capital contributed and available net debt for deployment to estimate the invested(able) capital (IC). This adjustment puts NXT's share price on ~1.0x EV/IC. Accordingly applying our target range of ~1.3x to ~1.5x EV/IC would imply ~$1.85 to ~$2.20 per share:

3) Base case DCF $2.05 + $0.20 replacement cost TV

Without assuming any terminal value for NXT's existing DCs, our base case model (using a ~10.3% WACC) generate a DCF of ~$2.05 per share.

Industry forecasts (discussed later) expects the outsourced colocation market segment to generate ~$1.7bn of revenue in 2020, spread amongst ~500k sqm of technical floor space. This implies ~$3.5k per sqm. Using the standard rack size and NXT's current rack power intensity (~2kW/sqm), the implied yield per MW would be ~$7m in FY20.

In comparison, our base case forecast assumes <$6m/MW average yield in FY20, and we estimate NXT's share price at ~$1.60-1.70 implies <$5m/MW. In short, we think this sensitivity suggests the implied volume (MW) and yield ($m/MW) profile in the current NXT share price looks overly conservative.

Figure 7: Sensitivity of DCF to FY15-20 MW contracting and yield profile (assuming no terminal value)

Source: UBSe

Practically, beyond the base-case project DCF, we think it is prudent to incorporate a terminal value for NXT's existing DCs based on % of future replacement cost. Around 40% of replacement cost is a reasonable level in our view, given 40-50% of new build is electrical and some 20-30% is mechanical, thus only a portion of this will need to completely replaced.

Using ~40% of future replacement cost as terminal value, we estimate the base-case DCF valuation for NXT at ~$2.25 per share.

Figure 8: Sensitivity of base-case DCF to terminal value and WACC %

Source: UBSe

Additional optionality exists

Potential new DC builds add option value

Above our base-case DCF, we think NXT also offers future upside optionality from potential new DC developments. NXT will likely need to raise debt and equity funding for such new developments, but assuming similar returns are achievable, the incremental capex should be valued at ~1.4-1.5x EV/IC.

At present, NXT has ~18% floor space share of the carrier neutral DC market and ~8% of the total outsourced colocation technical floor space. Colocation floor space is expected to grow at ~12% CAGR to 2020. On this basis we can extrapolate a few compounding scenarios:

Growth in line with the market: NXT maintaining its share of floor space implies ~40.5k sqm of technical space by FY20. Using NXT's current rack power density implies ~90MW total capacity, or an additional ~50MW build-out above NXT's current ~40MW theoretical capacity. Adding this capacity at ~$10m per MW would value the additional returns at ~$0.20-0.25.

Higher rack power density: If NXT can improve power efficiency and lift kW/rack density to 5kW or 6kW from ~4kW, sale of the additional DC build-out should generate an additional $0.25 to $0.50 of value.

More market share or higher Industry demand: Faster than expected colocation growth or market share gain by NXT (as a leading neutral DC provider) could also drive additional DC build-out requirements and add incremental returns.

Sensitivity to the above variables and corresponding upside are illustrated below:

Figure 9: Future option value ($/share): rack density vs. EV/IC and mkt share%

Source: UBSe

Overall we think ~$0.50 of optionality is reasonably feasible from new DC developments based on the above analysis. Particularly if factoring in:

Ongoing industry growth driven by adoption of cloud computing and power efficiency should lead to large neutral DCs consolidating market share.

NXT's power efficiency and density is likely to improve to meet the demand for greater volume of servers and computing / processing power.

Future re-gearing and capital management potential

In the initial construction phase, NXT depended heavily on equity funding and recycling capital via real estate sales.

As a stable revenue and EBITDA base is established from the existing DC utilisation, we expect NXT's OpFCF generation to be able to support higher gearing, which means management can optimise the existing capital structure or draw down debt for potential new DC development.

NXT recently signed ~$60m of unsecured 5-year senior notes at a fixed cost of ~9% (~8% coupon and ~1% accrued payable on redemption). This compares to Australian 5yr swap rates at ~3.4%, implying NXT is paying nearly ~600bps of margin. As another benchmark, UBS' Australia non-financial corporate bond index for BBB- rated entities is only yielding ~4.6%.

Figure 10: UBS Australia Index: 5yr BBB- Aus non-financial corporate bond yield

Source: UBS

Based on NXT's existing DC foot print and UBS forecasts, we believe NXT can more or less self-fund the remaining DC fit-out capex from internally generated cash-flow. Therefore aggressive drawn down of additional debt (above the current note facility) to support existing capital utilisation is unnecessary in our view.

Figure 11: NXT leverage (UBSe)

Source: UBSe

This means over the next ~5years, NXT's gearing metrics should begin to look increasingly conservative; particularly as the recurring revenue base expands. Assuming NXT is comfortable with net debt to EBITDA of ~2x (vs. Equinix geared at ~3x) we estimate NXT would have additional debt capacity of ~$190m by FY20.

Depending on the speed of NXT's revenue ramp-up, we see potential options emerging for reinvestment or capital management from rebalancing NXT's capital structure before FY20. For instance, additional gearing can be used to:

Fund new DC developments

Conduct share buyback or capital return to shareholders

Pay out special dividends (notwithstanding the lack of franking in our view)

 

NXT investment view recap

Invest a space & time continuum

Initiate with BUY (PT$2.25): Our NXT price-target of $2.25 is derived from on a base case DCF plus a terminal value.

NXT is entering the next stage of its life cycle as the initial DC construction phase ends and revenue build up starts to gain momentum. Therefore as an investment, we think NXT needs to be assessed from a highly fundamental perspective.

On balance significant valuation upside exists on a risk-reward basis over the next ~2 years in our view.

Figure 12: NXT valuation stack vs. current share price

Source: UBSe

Unique exposure to growth trends: NXT is one of the largest neutral data centres operators in Australia and the only operator with a national footprint.

The underlying thesis for investing in data centre colocation is driven by a number of structural trends which are changing how IT technology and services are consumed by private and public sectors. Consequently this leads to greater demand for colocation and data centre outsourcing. Specific trends include:

Data centre IP traffic is forecast to increase at +25-30% CAGR in APAC and globally.

Outsourcing/consolidation of smaller legacy DCs; the number of Aus data centres (majority computer rooms) is expected fall at a rate of ~30% over 3yrs.

Maturity in cloud technology and increased adoption of as-a-service delivery models via the cloud will drive demand for neutral colocation space.

More demanding power and cooling requirements have approached levels which make in-housed data centre solutions increasingly difficult to stack up economically.

Data centre ecosystems will be of growing importance for service providers, content providers, and various enterprise verticals.

NXT's underperformance in the past year offers an opportunity: NXT has underperformed the ASX Small-cap Industrials by ~40% over the past year.

Figure 13: NXT share price & relative performance since listing vs. ASX Small-cap industrials

Source: IRESS, UBS

We think this may be driven by a combination factor including:

Equity raising fatigue, leading to SPP withdrawal in Aug-13.

Timing of sell-down by founder Mr. Bevan Slattery (from ~14.6% to ~7.8%).

Softer than expected $m/MW performance due to white-space contracts.

Expectations for further equity raising (instead of the unsecured note issue).

Lower than consensus FY14 result and/or FY15 guidance.

We believe the above items are largely short-term focused and do not change our fundamental view of NXT's investment proposition in the long term. In the next ~12 months, in our view funding concerns around the existing DC footprint should reduce and NXT's focus on building revenue momentum via higher yielding rack sales should add comfort to the longer-term profitability outlook.

Steady flow of catalysts over next ~12 months: outside of announcing development & funding for new DC development(s), we do not expect any major step-change catalysts or announcements in the near-term. Instead we think a constant flow of news which increases confidence in NXT's revenue build-up momentum is more likely:

Ongoing customer and contract wins to lift growth in annualised contracted recurring revenue (ACRR).

Expected uplift in average price yield per MW via incremental retail rack sales.

NXT turning cash-flow +ive and EBITDA breakeven in FY15 will be a key milestone for the company and increase NXT's investment appeal in our view.

Potential contract wins from the Federal Government following inclusion of C1 on the government DC supplies panel in in Jul-14.

Update on process of new ancillary services / products to launch in FY15.

Indications around future potential to commission B2 in Brisbane driven by capacity shortage in B1 and customer demand.

Global peer valuation comps are difficult

Equinix (EQIX) listed on the NASDAQ has traditionally been the closest global peer for NXT in our view. However this is changing as EQIX is in the process of converting to a US REIT structure by Jan-15, which will allow ~90% pay-out of taxable earnings as a cash dividend (assuming >75% of earnings are from real estate activities). This process has been a driver behind EQIX's share price since mid-2012, and has arguably driven some re-rating in EQIX valuation.

Digital Realty (DLR) is another global name often compared with NXT; however DLR is a wholesale player in renting out DC space, not focused on interconnectivity or DCaaS. DLR operates under a US REIT structure and is effectively a specialised real estate developer, whereas EQIX still leases the majority of its DC sites.

Figure 14: Relative total return performance of NXT vs. EQIX and DLR over since Sep-11

Source: Datastream, UBS

These differences tax structure, business service offered, and business strategy makes direct comparison difficult against NXT in our view. In addition, NXT is in a much earlier stage of its life cycle compared to EQIX or DLR, as such spot trading multiples comps are also irrelevant given the expect revenue ramp-up from NXT (NXT has ive earnings and only expecting EBITDA breakeven in 1H15).

Figure 15: Consensus EQIX, DLR forward P/E big range

Source: Datastream, UBS

Currently both EQIX and DLR are trading at ~9x EBITDA; as a simple exercise if we apply ~9x EV/EBITDA to a FY20-22 (post ramp-up) NXT EBITDA estimate, and discount the EV back to FY15 using a ~10-11% WACC, the implied value / share for NXT would be $2.20 to $2.50.

Key investment risks

We think main risks associated with NXT include:

Ramp-up risk: slow down or falling sales momentum, resulting in lower than expected data centre utilisation in the next ~2-3 years. This would lead to material downside risk to UBS and consensus estimates.

Operational/reputational risks: specialised colocation providers typically offer uninterrupted connectivity and nearly >99% uptime. Operational disruption or unexpected outages may damage NXT's reputation and/or its industry certifications (UTI Tier III), leading to higher client churn.

Competitive risks: NXT competes with a number of large global DC operators in Australia. Suitable DC sites can be difficult to source and take ~1-2yr to construct, however increased competition from existing and new entrants cannot be ruled out over the medium term in our view.

Technology risks: Rapid change in technology - particularly related to power, cooling or storage efficiency - can reduce NXT's competitive advantages, leading to increased capex requirements or lower revenue yields.

Industry & business review

Company snapshot

NXT is Australia's leading DCaaS (Data-Centre-as-a-Service) colocation provider, operating data centres in 5 major capital cities. NXT is the only neutral provider with a national footprint.

NXT listed in Dec-2010 with the aim to develop the next generation of large scale data centres in Australia. Since then NXT has completed construction of all 5 data centres it currently operates. Funding has come from IPO proceeds, additional equity injections, capital recycling via sale-and-leaseback of land, and recently debt.

So what is a data centre?

Defining the modern DC

Data centres (DC) are defined as physical or virtual infrastructure used by enterprises (corporates, telco/carriers, or governments) to house computer hardware, server and networking systems and components for the enterprise's IT needs. This typically involves storing, processing and serving large amounts of mission-critical data to clients in a client/server architecture.

The newer generation of DC are designed to provide a secure and robust environment specifically designed to house the IT infrastructure of numerous customers (co-location).

Figure 23: Sample data centre layout

Source: NXT

A DC usually requires extensive backup power supply systems, cooling systems, redundant networking connections and state-of-the-art security systems. This is particularly the case for larger third party data centres which are highly specialised and secure buildings. Typically the IT equipment within may be owned and operated by either the user or the third party provider.

Figure 24: Key components of a modern DC

Source: UBS

 

Why choose colocation?

Co-location is the provision of space for a customers public or private network, and/or computer equipment on the co-location providers data centre premises. It allows the customer to retain full management responsibility for day-to-day running of their co-located equipment, while enjoying access to security-enhanced, reliable data centres and high-bandwidth connectivity.

A key benefit of colocation is the ability for peering (interconnectivity) between enterprises, telco/ISPs, content providers, IT system integrators/managed services, and other as-a-service vendors.

Peering is the practice of exchanging data traffic between the abovementioned parties, for example multiple telcos and content service providers using physical fibre connections (cross-connects) at a peering point. Most peering points are located in data centres, where the different network operators and service providers co-locate their Points-of-Presence.

Peering often provides a lower cost, lower latency route to a destination than otherwise reachable through alternatives (i.e. where one provider pays another to deliver traffic between its customers and the customers of other providers).

An example using content providers and telco/ISPs is illustrated below. The first diagram depicts internet connectivity between content providers via large telco/ISPs without peering. This arrangement involves one provider paying another (e.g. telco/ISP) to deliver traffic between its customers and the customers of other providers (i.e. via a public network such as the internet).

The second diagram depicts the peering situation involving the interconnectivity of providers to allow for data traffic to bypass the large telco/ISPs. This peering alternative thus provides a lower-cost, low latency route to the end destination.

Where does DCaaS fit in today's IT stack?

Data centres are becoming increasingly third-party operated, but the data centre concept itself has existed for as long as computer networks. In the broadest sense there are literally millions of data centres worldwide, but >90% of them are embedded in the IT operations of the organisations that generate and use the data stored (e.g. a computer room).

As IT consumption evolves towards multi-tier architectures, user organisations are choosing to 1) co-locate network hardware and latency-demanding servers near network nodes (e.g. point-of-presence / exchange), and/or 2) install larger scale storage / data banks via leasing white-space (e.g. large scale enterprise or managed services / ERP / CRM providers).

Specialised DC operators such as NXT provide the necessary technical infrastructure (technical floor space) to facilitate numerous other "as-a-service" delivery models by offering DC-as-a-service. Importantly, as a neutral DC provider in the IT stack, NXT's offering is agnostic to managed service providers, other as-a-service vendors, telcos, or enterprise customers.

Figure 27: Where NXT and DCaaS fits in the IT stack

Source: NXT

Data centre uptime tiering

A key industry certification for large colocation DCs is the Uptime Institute's tiers classification. Data centres are classified into 4 tiers defined by the maximum hours of downtime per year. This availability measure is itself the result of various design and operational aspects of the data centre. Out of NXT's five DCs, three (M1, S1 and P1) are Tier-3 certified.

Key data centre jargon list

Below we've outlined some of the key industry jargon related to DCs mentioned in our report and used by NXT.

(Blade) server: a small form-factor computer, commonly used in arrays mounted together in a frame that fits into a standard rack. Blades are narrower than standard 19-inch rack servers, but they contain most of the components of a complete computer.

Cross-connects / interconnects: A local fibre connection within at DC allowing customers to interconnect/peer with each-other, thereby enabling the DC as a hub or eco-system with close proximity to major external fibre routes and points or presence.

Power Usage Effectiveness (PUE): a ratio measuring the power feeding into the DC to the power consumed by the customer's IT equipment. An ideal 1.0 PUE ratio is practical impossibility because DC lighting and air-conditioning also use power, whilst a facility with a ratio of >3 is considered highly inefficient.

Rack(s): a globally standardised frame, ~19 inches (or 483mm) wide which houses a number of servers (up to 46).

Technical area: the revenue-generating raised floor space of a data centre (eg effective equivalent to lettable area).

Technical fit-out: the installation and fit out of technical data centre infrastructure including power supply, cooling, connectivity and security

White space: un-utilised space for customised hardware to be rented to (usually large) customers to install their own private data suites & cages.

Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS): UPS system or battery back-up, provides emergency power by supplying power from a separate source when utility power is unavailable. It differs from a standby generator, which does not provide instant protection from a momentary power interruption.

Industry landscape

What's a 'DC' but not a DC?

There are numerous ways to classify DCs; according to Gartner, Australia had about ~50k operating data centres at the end of 2012 (majority were single-site or computer rooms), but only 10 are large centres defined as having >1,000 racks or >1,800 sqm (i.e. roughly the size of NXT's smallest DC B1). By the end of 2013 there were ~64.5k data centres, of which ~53k are single-site and ~11k are computer rooms. Only ~240 DCs are classed as midsized, <90 as enterprise data centres (~250 racks), and only ~10 as 'large facilities'.

Large DC operating models

A more conventional categorisation employed by NXT classifies larger DCs into four groups. NXT is purely a Neutral DC operator in this context, and is not affiliated with any telco / service providers or bundled offerings.

Addressable market and positioning

There are a large number of DC operators in Australia including telcos, cloud-service providers and ICT providers. However in terms of large neutral DC operators who compete directly with NXT, the number becomes very limited.

Total 'DC' market size big, but less relevant: According to IBISWorld, the size of the DC market in Australia is ~$475m in FY14, with the largest DC players being Fujitsu and IBM. Other emerging players include Digital Realty, Equinix and NXT. According to BuddeComm, the DC industry revenue is ~$600m in 2012, of which ~30% is from managed-hosting and ~70% from colocation.

Both these definitions do not sufficiently differentiate the business nature of neutral DCs to represent NXT's addressable market in our view

Industry outlook

For Australia, Gartner predicted in 2013 the number of single site / small rack / computer room 'DC's to drop from ~64k to ~46k by 2015 (-30%), representing a significant change in how data is managed by enterprises and a shift (directly or indirectly) to collocation / outsourcing of in-housed DC functions.

In 2013 ~25% of Australian companies outsourced their DC requirements, while ~31% operated their own DC and ~24% relied on a combination of both (Gartner survey). More than half of those companies which outsourced did so due to cost savings, though other significant reasons include security, and complexity (required to maintain adequate DC infrastructure internally).

At the end of 2013 the colocation services market grew to ~$700m representing +17% growth over 2012, with the overall technical foot print increasing +16% by ~31k sqm. Industry forecasts from Frost&Sullivan expect +11.7% CAGR in total technical space from ~230k sqm in 2013 to ~500k sqm in 2017, accompanied by industry revenue CAGR of +13.9% to ~$1.7bn from ~$0.7bn.

Figure 38: Australian outsourced data centre industry outlook

Source: Frost & Sullivan: Australian Data Centre Services Market Report, 2014

Cost pressures are increasing, leading to demand for better management of power and cooling, as well as adoption of as-a-service offerings. Energy efficiency has also become a key component of organisational strategies in their approach to DCs, with customers often demanding datacentres which have <1.5 Power Utilisation Efficiency (PUE) rating.

Another recent trend in Australia is a shift towards integrated systems, or converged infrastructure servers, storage and networking converging into a single environment. This is also having an impact on the sort of data centres organisations require, how they power and cool them, how they segment the infrastructure within the data centre, and so on.

In addition to cost considerations, other structural changes are driving demand for the broader DC market including: 1) internet IP traffic growth, 2) increased adoption of outsourcing and the cloud, and 3) the development of enterprise ecosystem clusters. We discuss these drivers more in detail later in the report.

NXT business model run through

Revenue model

Core services: NXT offers different product packages depending on the customer type. 'Retail' offers typically refer to smaller scale contracts for racks or pods, while 'wholesale' deals typically refer to cages and suites. Specifically:

Rack: standardised frame housing up to 46 servers

Pod: small cluster of racks with physical security

Cage: space or group of racks surrounded by a physical cage

Suite: larger space or group of racks with a greater level of physical security, including high-grade enclosures, barriers to entry and monitoring

Other offerings: Other product/service offerings from NXT include:

Cross-connects: internal fibre connection between customer racks and an interconnection room (linking together the ecosystem).

Technical support services: NXT support desk and technician service calls on site

OneDC: client DC monitoring / management portal platform

In FY15, NXT is planning to launch a number of additional bundled rack / connectivity offering variations along with a SaaS version of the OneDC data centre management software portal.

Figure 39: NXT product portfolio

Source: NXT

Pricing: Neutral DC operators like NXT usually price using a combination of 1) rent for floor space (sqm or racks) and 2) power charge (per kW) for equipment usage. Pre-determined contract pricing escalation is usually inflation linked.

In recent years there has been a change in the pricing methodology of data centres from space being sold on per-rack or per sqm basis towards space being sold by kW (or power consumption).

Typically the rent charge is relatively fixed, whilst the power charge can vary. In effect, the power capacity utilised 1) drives the net effective revenue yield for NXT and 2) reflects the fit-out capex required to deliver the necessary infrastructure to support the power density.

Other NXT revenues include establishment fees and projects fees for customer support to setup (non-recurring), and service fees if the customer requires NXT engineers for service calls and onsite support (deemed recurring by NXT).

Sales 'go-to-market' model

Contract structure: Neutral DC customers typically sign service agreements for terms of >3 years plus options to extend. Wholesale white space contracts are usually more bespoke and priced lower given scale, and retail rack deals are based on standard pricing. Customer payments are made monthly.

Sales channels: NXT employs "sell-with", "sell-through", and "sell-to" channels to market to leverage its reseller and service provider partnerships.

Figure 41: NXT sales channel programme

Key customers: Of the total ~302 Master-Service-Agreements NXT has signed as at Jun-14, ~165 are classified as channel partners (as-a-service providers), of which ~46 are telcos. For instance, both Telstra and Optus partner with NXT to bundled DC colocation into their own offerings.

NXT is focused on gaining exposure to cloud-computing / IT service outsourcing via creating ecosystems supported by key as-a-service vendors. This strategy is achieving critical mass to attract retail rack volume resold through numerous channel partners. For NXT's channel partners, NXT's unique national footprint, vendor neutrality and rack price parity are attractive partnership characteristics.

Capex model

Quasi-infrastructure FCF profile: DCs exhibit infrastructure-like free-cash-flow attributes in our view. Unlike traditional utilities or transport infrastructure where relative certainty around volume or pricing (or both) exists, DCs on average face greater revenue risks given they are neither monopolistic nor regulated.

However DCs face higher revenue risks given they are neither monopolistic nor regulated. Nevertheless we recognise a DC does have characteristics which reduce revenue volatility once it is sufficiently contracted (the sticky network nature of customers, capex & location barriers for new builds, and the economies of scale in operating costs). In essence, a DC's theoretical FCF profile over its asset life should be similar to a typical infrastructure asset in our view. Similarities include:

Heavy upfront construction and/or capacity fit-out capex in the first few years.

Initial sales from signing foundation customers can produce low revenue yields, but this should improve as the DC ecosystem gains critical mass

Relatively fixed cost base results in material operating leverage as capital utilisation increases, followed by stable CPI linked pricing and cost escalation.

Maintenance capex and O&M costs represent a low % of revenue and deprecation (without assuming additional capex to extend useful life).

Growth capex: We estimate the cost to fit-out DC capacity is now roughly ~$9-10m per MW, broadly split as:

Recently NXT announced plans to create ~5MW of incremental capacity within its existing DC footprint via innovative engineering and design (ProjectPlus) without the need for additional fit-out capex. The resulting capacity uplift expected in M1, S1 and P1 will materially reduce the remaining fit-out capex/MW to <$7m (UBSe).

This is a significant development in our view, because for infrastructure-like-assets a key lever to lifting project returns is to lower upfront capex to achieve the same asset-life FCF generation.

Figure 52: UBSe NXT capex profile over ~25 yr DC asset life assumed

Source: UBSe

Maintenance capex: Consistent with the economic model for infrastructure, we think a DC's FCF profile (assuming finite asset life) is likely to be materially above NPAT to reflect lower maintenance capex versus accounting depreciation.

This is largely due to the heavy capex upfront, and the need to recover the return-on-capital and return-of-capital from the project over a finite period. Given NXT's DCs are still in the initial years of their life cycle, the level of FCF drain from future maintenance capex is not yet evident and difficult to forecast. We've assumed NXT spends ~40-50% of depreciation on maintenance capex from FY20.

This appears more conservative than EQIX, which spends ~2% of revenue on maintenance capex (EQIX's depreciation is ~20-25% of revenue; implying maintenance capex is only ~10% of depreciation). However accounting policy on whether to capitalise maintenance expense can causes optical differences.

Dissecting NXT forecasts

Group level forecast by phase

Breakeven in FY15 to mark a milestone: our estimates are in line with NXT guidance for EBITDA breakeven in 1H15 and a +ive EBITDA contribution in 2H15 (UBSe ~$1.8m). We also expect OpCF pre-capex to turn +ive in FY15. Our FY15 forecasts reflect:

DC revenue of $53.0m in line with guidance of $51-55m (excluding any large wholesale contracts) and sale of ~2.8MW (vs. guidance of 2.4-3.0MW).

Fixed costs (facility & corporate overheads) of $44.5m vs. $44m-$46.5m (this excludes power, which UBSe at ~13% of DC revenue in FY15).

Capex of ~$32m (guidance $30-35m) including non-fit-out growth capex to drive ancillary revenues and DC operationally efficiencies.

Maintenance capex: 4-6% of revenue spent on maintenance capex in the long-term, conservatively reflecting ~0.4-0.5x depreciation.

8 key thematic drivers

1) Increasing traffic & connectivity

Cisco forecasts total global and APAC IP traffic to grow at around ~21% CAGR to 2018 from 2013. The projected growth is primarily driven by the explosion of mobile data usage, increased connectivity, outsourcing of storage, and consumption of media content.

Figure 71: Global IP traffic forecast to 2018 (& CAGR%)

Source: Cisco

As the internet grows in size and the number of users and frequency of use increases, telcos, ISPs, and other public network operators need to exchange / peer increasing amounts of traffic.

It is important to recognise that since 2008, quantitatively, the majority of internet traffic originated and/or terminated in some sort of DC somewhere. As of 2012, ~76% of total DC data traffic actually occurs within the DC, which already dwarves traffic flow externally (what is usually defined as internet IP and WAN).

Cisco forecasts published in 2012 suggests that by 2017, traffic within DCs will remain the majority type dominating total data centre traffic flows.

Figure 72: Global data centre traffic break-down

 

Figure 73: Data Centre IP traffic 2012-2017e (EB/yr)

 

Source: Cisco

 

Source: Cisco

2) Neutrality is important for fostering ecosystems

Figure 74: NXT customer mix

Source: NXT

Simplistically speaking, the internet is based on exchange points where traffic between ISPs can be passed on (i.e. a network of networks). As traffic increases, so will demand for connectivity (peering) between the numerous independent sub-networks that make up the whole.

Historically, these exchange points (or points of presence) were managed by carriers without network neutrality, which are leading to conflicts of interests particularly as telcos move from being infrastructure providers to content providers. Given alternative duplication of such networks and connectivity are costly, neutral colocation DC providers have an increasingly important role to play in our view.

Neutral DCs located in key network hubs/nodes offer connectivity to multiple network providers and end-user organisations by providing interconnections (via selling cross-connects at high margins). This interconnectivity amongst service/content providers or within particular industry verticals (e.g. financial institutions) subsequently creates valuable ecosystems (a network effect) that lead to stickiness of the customer base. The benefits of the ecosystem (i.e. significant access and latency benefits) increases as the number of cross-connects increase.

Examples of potential industry verticals hosted by neutral DCs include managed / network service providers, SaaS providers, financial services, and media content providers. In essence within the ecosystem, connectivity in a cluster can be established with business partners, suppliers, ISPs, customers, even competitors.

Figure 75: DC ecosystems latency vs. criticality

Source: EQIX

 

3) Relevance of the 'cloud'

Cloud computing can be broken up into cloud infrastructure, private cloud and public cloud.

Cloud Infrastructure services refer to cloud applications operated internally for and managed by the end user. Private cloud refers to the outsourcing of cloud infrastructure to a third party. Public cloud is similar to private cloud, but rather than customers having dedicated cloud infrastructure, they share those resources with others.

Figure 76: In-house vs. colocation vs. cloud options & drivers

Source: Deloitte, NXT

For listed DCs such as NXT, frequent concerns are raised around whether the rise of cloud computing poses risks to DC revenues (particularly private cloud hosting services offered by Amazon for example).

On the contrary, we believe the growth of cloud service vendors will not replace colocation, but operate in parallel as a different (intermediated) service stack that still ultimately require colocation by the as-a-service provider.

The same question of "who is cannibalised by Amazon-Web-Services wholesale data centres (e.g. Digital Realty) or retail rack data centres (Equinix)" has been asked before in the US.

The answer is simple there is no categorical cannibalisation. We acknowledge the colocation market is highly segmented, but the requirements of many enterprises are not colocation OR cloud but more often colocation AND cloud.

Furthermore, AWS is one of Equinix's largest customers. Amazon uses Equinix to host some of their Direct Connect PoPs. Direct Connect is essentially a private peering switch that connects directly to the AWS infrastructure, allowing AWS to bypass the public internet and interconnect with DCs. This is important as by bypassing the public internet, the customers can ensure less potential problems and greater performance which can enhance AWS performance.

Having an anchor client like AWS to establish the eco-system allows the DC operator to move away from selling large white-space (technical footprint) to focus on selling retail racks who want to interconnect within the facility. In essence, cloud services (such as AWS) are taking share from traditional managed service / hosting providers, which is a separate category from colocation operators.

Broadly speaking, cloud computing has a two impacts on DC demand.

Increases demand for DC space as cloud technology matures and as an increasing number of service providers start offering cloud based services.

Cloud computing leads to improved server utilisation through virtualisation and consolidation of storage infrastructure, thereby resulting in reduced demand for in-house space in the long run.

In short, migration into the cloud should ultimately increase neutral DC traffic. This is illustrated by Cisco's forecast for global cloud traffic within DCs, which is expected to increase at +35% CAGR from 2012 to 2017, compared to traditional DC traffic CAGR of +12%. This is marginally higher in the APAC region, where Cisco thinks DC's cloud traffic is growing by +42% CAGR vs. traditional traffic at +14%:

Figure 77: Cloud vs. traditional data centre traffic from 2012-2017

Source: Cisco

In the ANZ region, IDC forecasts cloud computing market growth at ~25.5% from 2013 to 2018 from ~A$0.9bn to ~A$2.7bn. Already we've seen adoption of infrastructure-as-a-service double in 2013 in Australia, and ample anecdotal evidence of the momentum building in cloud adoption:

Launch of Australian data centres by Amazon Web Services and Rackspace, and plans by Microsoft to follow.

Telstra reported cloud revenues are growing at >30%.

The Aus government's DCaaS multi-use list (whole-of-government head agreement) has been used for >20 cloud purchases in its first year since Oct-12.

Increasing adoption of SaaS up the IT stack (Google Apps, Office 365, NetSuite, SalesForce)

 

4) Colocation relatively agnostic to changing ERP

Gartner forecasts by 2016, heavily customised on-premise ERP solutions will effectively be 'legacy' ERP. In conjunction, by 2018 Gartner expects ~30% of service enterprises will move ERP applications into the cloud. The rest of the ERP suites within organisations will loosely move to a 'hybrid ERP' model, comprising some functions delivered via cloud services (public or private) and some maintained on-premises (likely core ERP functions such as financial management).

Further ahead, in 10+ years Gartner foresees ERP solutions migrating completely into the cloud, which will by then deliver best-practice but relatively commoditised ERP processes.

While the gradual migration to full cloud based ERP solution may not represent an immediate sea change for pure cloud-based solution providers in the next ~3 years, we think DC operators such as NXT remain agnostic to the exact service delivery model.

As long as incremental migration of ERP functions is continuing (centralised directly or indirectly via third party IT stack vendors), colocation should benefit as a result.

Figure 78: Hybrid cloud model

Source: UBS

 

5) Importance of efficiency and low PUE

Power density refers to the kW/rack a DC is able to support. It is effectively a measure of the DC's power infrastructure (and cooling capability).

Higher powered infrastructure requirements are driven by increases in the number of co-located servers and the increased sophistication of the servers. Importantly, the demand for power and cooling will be difficult for older legacy data centres to handle. Because power and cooling are a key factor in pricing retail rack colocation, demand for more efficient colocation services should support a relatively robust pricing environment for newer DCs in our view.

Results from a global study conducted by DatacentreDynamics (DCD) in 2011 suggests once power consumption per rack exceeds ~5kW per rack, the operating cost and funding requirements to host the racks in-house increases to a point where outsourcing becomes evidently economical. As such, ~5kW is a considered a rule-of-thumb driving colocation demand. Given the relatively high electricity and labour prices in Australia, it is highly likely this rule is also applicable in our view.

The average age of an Australian datacentre is >18 years, dating back to mid-90s. Since 2000, the average number of servers per rack has increased by >50%, primarily driven by the increased adoption of new denser hardware (blade servers), putting existing in-housed small-scale rack infrastructure under increasing pressure.

At the DC level, the measure of PUE (Power Usage Effectiveness) reflects the ratio of the total power load the DC relative to the load used by customers. This is a key measure for a DC's competitiveness given facility power and cooling are key inputs into co-location pricing. The average PUE of data centres in Australia is ~2.25 according to a 2013 Digital Realty survey. This compares to NXT's target weighted average PUE of ~1.9 in FY14 and target of ~1.4 (as capital utilisation increases).

Figure 79: Aus DC PUEs (survey of IT decision marker in 2013)

Source: Digital Realty

 

6) More co-location is on the way

The increasing capex and costs to run in-housed DCs is leading to outsourcing to neutral co-location providers with more efficient DC footprint and operational scale. Most office buildings are not equipped to accommodate data centres. For example, a commercial building is unable to support large volumes of racks in a limited space; temperature regulated by the centralised cooling systems installed for human occupation is too high, and power supply density is too low.

In a recent surveyed conducted by Digital Realty in 2012/13, nearly ~50% of respondents indicated they are considering two or more methods to expand their DC capacity, including ~33% looking at rack colocation and ~44% looking at leasing whitespace.

7) Data sovereignty concerns benefit locals

The most obvious technical argument for hosting cloud services in an Australian based data centre is improved latency. But concerns over data sovereignty (i.e. whether private data will be legally or illegally accessible by governments or other third parties) remain a key issue for Australian enterprises.

As more Australian companies adopt some form of cloud computing, greater volumes of their data are being stored and shared with various third party vendors around the globe, particularly in areas under US jurisdiction.

In recent years, revelations from leaks on how US government surveillance programmes monitor public network data have only fuelled the debate. For example, the collection of Internet traffic data from major American cloud companies including Google and Microsoft by the NSA using the Patriot Act 2001.

Exact legal ramifications around the issue can be complex depending on the type of data and exactly where and how it is stored. However Australian companies are becoming more active in trying to understand and plan around the sovereignty issue. Basically when data is in the cloud, it is broadly considered to be under the jurisdiction of where the data is physically hosted, subject to local laws and regulation. Given the legal uncertainty and concerns from the local client base, Australian based cloud providers are making efforts to setup data centres onshore.

In Australia, from March-14 changes to the Privacy Act will require organisations that use data storage outside of Australia to disclose (in their privacy policy) which country is hosting those servers. In addition, before an organisation can disclose personal information to a cloud provider overseas, it must take reasonable steps to ensure that the recipient will not breach 'Privacy Principles' (e.g. via contractual arrangements, or if the cloud service provider is subject to similar privacy laws).

Overall the level of clarity on how to adhere to these new rules in Australia remains low and untested.

For example, unlike Australia, other developed jurisdictions often distinguish between the obligations of a data controller (an entity that actively controls personal information and how it is used) and a data processor (entities that only processes personal information as directed by the data controller). Therefore it is arguable that the new Australian rule could mean an IaaS provider may be subject to same obligations more appropriately for a SaaS provider for instance.

 

8) Having a national DC footprint makes sense

Not only are organisations based in Australia demanding onshore data centres, they also frequently demand dual locations. For example, IBM recently announced plans to open in two co-located data centres in Australia (i.e. outsourced space via neutral DCs); its Melbourne DC location will begin operating in a matter of weeks, while a Sydney site will be open by the end of the year.

Similarly, Microsoft is also planning to open dual Azure centres in Melbourne and Sydney later this year (again via neutral DC colocation). Amazon Web Services has been operating in Sydney Equinix's DC since 2012, but also launched in Melbourne in July this year. The colocation provider(s) for IBM and Microsoft are undisclosed.

One key factor driving the need for 2 DC locations for large as-a-service providers is Australias geography and the need to provide recovery locations that are far enough from each other by distance. In Asia, if Hong Kong fails the redundancy can switch over to Singapore and vice versa. But in Australia if a sole DC fails, backup via Hong Kong or Singapore could cause major latency issues.

In this context we think NXT is well positioned as the only neutral DC provider with a presence in 5 major capital cities. As highlighted by the Digital Realty survey responses below, potential enterprise customers are increasingly look to utilise multiple colocations DCs.

Figure 84: Survey - number of locations planned for DC expansion 2013 vs 2014

Source: Digital Realty

Statement of Risk

Key risks for investing in NXT include revenue ramp-up risk (slow than expected DC sales momentum, operational / reputational risks (due to unexpected service disruptions or outages), competition risks (from existing or new entrants to the neutral DC segment), and technology risks (adverse changes in power, cooling or storage efficiencies).
